    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "1bc7996159c7ad2f",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "1bc7996159c7ad2f",
        "text": "You ask a very important question: Why do any of us cooperate? It is maybe always for a range of things. Often the real reasons are hidden, What I call hidden variables. All I can share is what I have experienced and observed. It is letting go of my belief in my separation from the horse. I think the horse is more open to being in that state (maybe) but is a prey animal so very reactive and fearful."
      },
      "after": "4065b529c334fc01",
      "date": 1693782657387
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
        "text": "I know the horse is way more powerful than me. He has to become coherent with himself and I have to be coherent with myself to connect. If I am not in that state I do not ride. The way I achieve this is by putting myself onto a pattern with no change. For dressage, that is a circle. The pace will be appropriate for the horse. Some horses find coherence in trot, others in canter. In my experience few achieve this in walk. The horse has to be coherent to have a good walk, which is why all dressage tests include \"free walk on a long rein\" and \"collected walk\". The circle helps us to maintain movement on a pattern with no change. \n\nThe rider/trainer/leader pays a lot of attention to the rhythm. It is like a metronome - putting horse and rider into a \"zen\" state. The whole task is about letting go and allowing this natural restful but alert state to occur. It is pure bliss. It feels completely safe and easy. That is why the horse wants to be there. It's why the rider wants to be there too! But few have ever felt it. Why? Because it can't be achieved by striving/effort or wanting! That is the secret. We believe that work should be effort but effort causes tension and there is no tension in this system at all.\n\nI've realised recently that what I have always been seeking is connection. When we have it everything is possible/viable, without it nothing is.  It always has been even as a child. I didn't find it in human company. Animals were much more open to it. I've noticed how each partner in a couple is often more open to it with their dog than with each other. Why is this? Why are we afraid to be\nknown by another human?"
      },
      "after": "1bc7996159c7ad2f",
      "date": 1693782664332
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "55994d55795f0597",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "55994d55795f0597",
        "text": "The challenge for the horse/rider system is maintaining this. In the moment that my attention wanders it is already lost. The thing that diverts me is always a speck of fear . The amazing thing I have learnt from horses is about my own attention and its links to tension. This is personal mastery of the highest level. I think that two ingredients are required to put a system on high performance: Power and Coherence (felt as tension in muscles and/or agitation mentally.) In a horse we call this  \"collection\". The issue is that power and coherence are interrelated. Too much power can result in loss of coherence. It is best to start with low levels of power and experiment with what more power does to coherence. Managing this balance is THE challenge. Put another way, we make haste slowly as I heard Robert Hall say:  http://kerry.tries.fed.wiki/view/emperors-new-clothes\n\nI met an amazing horseman in France, committed to pushing the boundaries of the horse/rider performance system and exploring how via experiential learning of the highest level. His name is Willy Sidorak and I am taking Marc to meet him in October. I did a project with Willy to capture his approach. You can read about it here: http://kerry.tries.fed.wiki/view/saving-tamtam. For many riders the horse is a dispensable tool of the trade and Willy has rehabilitated a lot of these horses. He has also rehabilitated people: Another dispensable tool of the trade for many business systems. Willy talks about connection as Love. It appears humans are actually afraid of Love. Can we love all creatures? I know I can connect with the ones that are open to it when I am open too.\n\nThere is always effort and work of course. It is hard physical work looking after horses but good riding should not be so. The rider gets her riding fitness from yard work not from riding! I wrote about this in an article for UK magazine, Horse &  Rider, titled \" How to improve your riding without riding!\" See http://kerry.tries.fed.wiki/view/writing-about-equines.\n\nThe competition dressage test is a test of the partnership's (organisation's) ability to maintain balance through increasingly difficult transitions ie frequency of changes of direction and pace. For many this is overwhelming - especially if done \"mechanically\". It cannot be achieved mechanically. When it is there is no beauty (harmony.) There is effort and fatigue. It is the same with our human organisations.\n\n Dressage judges mark the parts. The audience \"marks\" the whole! And sometimes we find it remarkable! The sight/feel of the whole that I am witnessing gives me bliss/wonder/awe. We are all programmed to recognise coherence. It is what we call beauty and vitality.  There are signs in the parts when I look at them eg, floppy relaxed ears, glassy relaxed eyes, a softly swishing tail moving in time with rhythm, fluidity of movement. So, the horse goes into what I call a blank cheque state of pure vulnerability and finds not fear but safety.  Take a look at these videos:  http://kerry.tries.fed.wiki/view/dressage-tests.Which of these do you find more beautiful? Why?\n\nYou talk about discord as a homeostat. I experienced dissonance with some trainers I visited with my horse. They would be telling me that what they were seeing was good but I felt bad. I couldn't understand it and felt it was maybe a problem with my judgement. Most trainers are not open to a discussion about why this is in my experience. I would get excluded for asking this question.\n\nLet me finish by saying thank you for prompting this exploration. It is difficult to capture any of this in words as it is about felt experiences and patterns of experiences. I have attempted to capture the more exploratory parts in italics. I would love to talk with you about this in real time. I know a number of people in a group I am in are similarly curious about the horse rider system as a metaphor. Maybe we could all explore together?\n\nPS I am going to be daring and say something that maybe I shouldn't. Maybe the only time most humans experience this is in orgasm. But orgasm is a rush of coherent bliss that dissipates quickly. I guess good horse riding is playing with connection, so ,continuing the sex metaphor, it is like good foreplay. Again we can have sex mechanically seeking an orgasm (and a lot of humans do) or we can quite literally make love....this takes longer and doesn't always achieve orgasm. In my experience if we seek an orgasm we rarely achieve it.  I don't think it is only riders that haven't experienced it. I think it is a lot of people (women!)"
      },
      "after": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "date": 1693782666880
