        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "f5ae95826d1a25c9",
        "text": "There is always effort and work of course. It is hard physical work looking after horses but good riding should not be so. The rider gets her riding fitness from yard work not from riding! I wrote about this in an article for UK magazine, Horse &  Rider, titled \" How to improve your riding without riding!\" See http://kerry.tries.fed.wiki/view/writing-about-equines.\n\nThe competition dressage test is a test of the partnership's (organisation's) ability to maintain balance through increasingly difficult transitions ie frequency of changes of direction and pace. For many this is overwhelming - especially if done \"mechanically\". It cannot be achieved mechanically. When it is there is no beauty (harmony.) There is effort and fatigue. It is the same with our human organisations.\n\n Dressage judges mark the parts. The audience \"marks\" the whole! And sometimes we find it remarkable! The sight/feel of the whole that I am witnessing gives me bliss/wonder/awe. We are all programmed to recognise coherence. It is what we call beauty and vitality.  There are signs in the parts when I look at them eg, floppy relaxed ears, glassy relaxed eyes, a softly swishing tail moving in time with rhythm, fluidity of movement. So, the horse goes into what I call a blank cheque state of pure vulnerability and finds not fear but safety.  Take a look at these videos:  http://kerry.tries.fed.wiki/view/dressage-tests.Which of these do you find more beautiful? Why?\n\nYou talk about discord as a homeostat. I experienced dissonance with some trainers I visited with my horse. They would be telling me that what they were seeing was good but I felt bad. I couldn't understand it and felt it was maybe a problem with my judgement. Most trainers are not open to a discussion about why this is in my experience. I would get excluded for asking this question.\n\nLet me finish by saying thank you for prompting this exploration. It is difficult to capture any of this in words as it is about felt experiences and patterns of experiences. I have attempted to capture the more exploratory parts in italics. I would love to talk with you about this in real time. I know a number of people in a group I am in are similarly curious about the horse rider system as a metaphor. Maybe we could all explore together?\n\nPS I am going to be daring and say something that maybe I shouldn't. Maybe the only time most humans experience this is in orgasm. But orgasm is a rush of coherent bliss that dissipates quickly. I guess good horse riding is playing with connection, so ,continuing the sex metaphor, it is like good foreplay. Again we can have sex mechanically seeking an orgasm (and a lot of humans do) or we can quite literally make love....this takes longer and doesn't always achieve orgasm. In my experience if we seek an orgasm we rarely achieve it.  I don't think it is only riders that haven't experienced it. I think it is a lot of people (women!)"
      },
      "after": "615c0a275dca00f9",
      "date": 1693782746622
