    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "1bc7996159c7ad2f",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "1bc7996159c7ad2f",
        "text": "# Why do any of us cooperate?"
      },
      "date": 1694523756033
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "414d99a49aa128d0",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "414d99a49aa128d0",
        "text": "# How do we connect with a horse?"
      },
      "date": 1694523765571
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
        "text": "I know the horse is way more **powerful** than me. He has to become coherent with himself and I have to be coherent with myself to connect. If I am not in that state I do not ride. The way I achieve this is by putting myself onto a pattern with no change. For dressage, that is a circle. The pace will be appropriate for the horse. Some horses find coherence in trot, others in canter. In my experience few achieve this in walk. The horse has to be coherent to have a good walk, which is why all dressage tests include \"free walk on a long rein\" and \"collected walk\". The circle helps us to maintain movement on a pattern with no change. \n\nThe rider/trainer/leader pays a lot of attention to the rhythm. It is like a metronome - putting horse and rider into a \"zen\" state. The whole task is about letting go and allowing this natural restful but alert state to occur. It is pure bliss. It feels completely safe and easy. That is why the horse wants to be there. It's why the rider wants to be there too! But few have ever felt it. Why? Because it can't be achieved by striving/effort or wanting! That is the secret. We believe that work should be effort but effort causes tension and there is no tension in this system at all.\n\nI've realised recently that what I have always been seeking is connection. When we have it everything is possible/viable, without it nothing is.  It always has been even as a child. I didn't find it in human company. Animals were much more open to it. I've noticed how each partner in a couple is often more open to it with their dog than with each other. Why is this? Why are we afraid to be\nknown by another human?"
      },
      "date": 1694523807588
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
        "text": "I know the horse is way more **powerful** than me. He has to become **coherent** with himself and I have to be coherent with myself to connect. If I am not in that state I do not ride. The way I achieve this is by putting myself onto a pattern with no change. For dressage, that is a circle. The pace will be appropriate for the horse. Some horses find coherence in trot, others in canter. In my experience few achieve this in walk. The horse has to be coherent to have a good walk, which is why all dressage tests include \"free walk on a long rein\" and \"collected walk\". The circle helps us to maintain movement on a pattern with no change. \n\nThe rider/trainer/leader pays a lot of attention to the rhythm. It is like a metronome - putting horse and rider into a \"zen\" state. The whole task is about letting go and allowing this natural restful but alert state to occur. It is pure bliss. It feels completely safe and easy. That is why the horse wants to be there. It's why the rider wants to be there too! But few have ever felt it. Why? Because it can't be achieved by striving/effort or wanting! That is the secret. We believe that work should be effort but effort causes tension and there is no tension in this system at all.\n\nI've realised recently that what I have always been seeking is connection. When we have it everything is possible/viable, without it nothing is.  It always has been even as a child. I didn't find it in human company. Animals were much more open to it. I've noticed how each partner in a couple is often more open to it with their dog than with each other. Why is this? Why are we afraid to be\nknown by another human?"
      },
      "date": 1694523824840
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
        "text": "I know the horse is way more **powerful** than me. He has to become **coherent** with himself and I have to be coherent with myself to connect. If I am not in that state I do not ride."
      },
      "date": 1694523839755
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "26e6ab668b3f802d",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "26e6ab668b3f802d",
        "text": "The way I achieve this is by putting myself onto a pattern with no change. For dressage, that is a circle. The pace will be appropriate for the horse. Some horses find coherence in trot, others in canter. In my experience few achieve this in walk. The horse has to be coherent to have a good walk, which is why all dressage tests include \"free walk on a long rein\" and \"collected walk\". The circle helps us to maintain movement on a pattern with no change. \n\nThe rider/trainer/leader pays a lot of attention to the rhythm. It is like a metronome - putting horse and rider into a \"zen\" state. The whole task is about letting go and allowing this natural restful but alert state to occur. It is pure bliss. It feels completely safe and easy. That is why the horse wants to be there. It's why the rider wants to be there too! But few have ever felt it. Why? Because it can't be achieved by striving/effort or wanting! That is the secret. We believe that work should be effort but effort causes tension and there is no tension in this system at all.\n\nI've realised recently that what I have always been seeking is connection. When we have it everything is possible/viable, without it nothing is.  It always has been even as a child. I didn't find it in human company. Animals were much more open to it. I've noticed how each partner in a couple is often more open to it with their dog than with each other. Why is this? Why are we afraid to be\nknown by another human?"
      },
      "after": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "date": 1694523840856
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "00e20a087cbc43f3",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "00e20a087cbc43f3",
        "text": "# How do we achieve coherence?"
      },
      "after": "79aeb91587d05bdb",
      "date": 1694523868759
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "26e6ab668b3f802d",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "26e6ab668b3f802d",
        "text": "The way I achieve this is by putting myself onto a pattern with no change. For dressage, that is a circle. It is the only shape with no change. The pace will be appropriate for the horse. Some horses find coherence in trot, others in canter. In my experience few achieve this in walk. The horse has to be coherent to have a good walk, which is why all dressage tests include \"free walk on a long rein\" and \"collected walk\". The circle helps us to maintain movement on a pattern with no change. \n\nThe rider/trainer/leader pays a lot of attention to the rhythm. It is like a metronome - putting horse and rider into a \"zen\" state. The whole task is about letting go and allowing this natural restful but alert state to occur. It is pure bliss. It feels completely safe and easy. That is why the horse wants to be there. It's why the rider wants to be there too! But few have ever felt it. Why? Because it can't be achieved by striving/effort or wanting! That is the secret. We believe that work should be effort but effort causes tension and there is no tension in this system at all.\n\nI've realised recently that what I have always been seeking is connection. When we have it everything is possible/viable, without it nothing is.  It always has been even as a child. I didn't find it in human company. Animals were much more open to it. I've noticed how each partner in a couple is often more open to it with their dog than with each other. Why is this? Why are we afraid to be\nknown by another human?"
      },
      "date": 1694523916877
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "26e6ab668b3f802d",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "26e6ab668b3f802d",
        "text": "The way I achieve this is by putting myself onto a pattern with no change. For dressage, that is a circle. It is the only shape with no change."
      },
      "date": 1694523923975
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "dfa750ba324d7b53",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "dfa750ba324d7b53",
        "text": "The pace will be appropriate for the horse. Some horses find coherence in trot, others in canter. In my experience few achieve this in walk. The horse has to be coherent to have a good walk, which is why all dressage tests include \"free walk on a long rein\" and \"collected walk\". The circle helps us to maintain movement on a pattern with no change. \n\nThe rider/trainer/leader pays a lot of attention to the rhythm. It is like a metronome - putting horse and rider into a \"zen\" state. The whole task is about letting go and allowing this natural restful but alert state to occur. It is pure bliss. It feels completely safe and easy. That is why the horse wants to be there. It's why the rider wants to be there too! But few have ever felt it. Why? Because it can't be achieved by striving/effort or wanting! That is the secret. We believe that work should be effort but effort causes tension and there is no tension in this system at all.\n\nI've realised recently that what I have always been seeking is connection. When we have it everything is possible/viable, without it nothing is.  It always has been even as a child. I didn't find it in human company. Animals were much more open to it. I've noticed how each partner in a couple is often more open to it with their dog than with each other. Why is this? Why are we afraid to be\nknown by another human?"
      },
